\b0 \cf0 They draw links between companies and republics, extremes being a democracy or a dictatorship. \
The main question they ask is: is there a relationship between shareholder rights and corporate performance\
They empirically study the link between their shareholder index and corporate performance. \'93long-run event study\'94.\
\'93Democracies\'94 earned significantly higher returns, were valued more highly and had better operating performance. \
Didn\'92t use random assignment, thus cannot make claims of causality\
\
In section 2 they detail the provisions\
Their index is a proxy for the balance of power between shareholders and managers\
For every firm they award a point for every provision that reduces shareholder rights. \
They state that it is obvious in most cases when this has occurred, ambiguous cases are discussed\
\
In section 3 they document the main empirical relationships \
Using performance-attribution time-series regressions \
They primarily find that companies in the lowest decile of their index outperform those in the higher decile by a statistically significant 8.4% per year. \
They state that in 1990 a one-point difference in the index was negatively associated with an 11.4% difference in Tobins Q \
	This seems pretty huge\
\
In section 4 they present some reasons why they might have found the above \
They are\
	weak shareholder rights caused additional costs, which could be underestimated by the market. If this occurs, a firms stock returns and operating perforate would have been worse than expected and the firms value at the beginning of the period would have been too high.\
	Managers in the 1980\'92s predicted poor performance in the 90\'92s but investors didn\'92t. In this case, managers could have put governance provisions in place to protect their jobs. this might have had real protective power, but would not have caused the poor performance. \
	the governance provisions did not cause poor performance, but rather were correlated with other characteristics that were associated with abnormal returns in the 1990\'92s. \
